00:18:00.939 --> 00:18:03.379
which are very much about what is happening in this world

529
00:18:03.379 --> 00:18:05.178
and what will happen in the future.

530
00:18:05.178 --> 00:18:07.039
And maybe psychic dreams in the sense that you are

531
00:18:07.039 --> 00:18:09.559
seeing quite clearly things that are distant from you.

532
00:18:09.559 --> 00:18:11.499
And then there are the dreams that are the experiences

533
00:18:11.499 --> 00:18:13.239
of a separate reality all together.

534
00:18:13.239 --> 00:18:16.039
And these, for active dreamers, are the most interesting.

535
00:18:16.039 --> 00:18:18.298
You've given some examples from your own life.

536
00:18:18.298 --> 00:18:21.199
We dream of other times and other lifetimes too,

537
00:18:21.199 --> 00:18:23.319
and from this we may or may not evolve some theory

538
00:18:23.319 --> 00:18:25.817
about our relationship with past or future lives.

539
00:18:25.817 --> 00:18:28.178
I dreamed all my life, for example, of a life which,

540
00:18:28.178 --> 00:18:30.318
a parallel Robert, not in his present body,

541
00:18:30.318 --> 00:18:34.057
is living in Britain and in Europe during World War II.

542
00:18:34.057 --> 00:18:35.258
I've dreamed this all of my life,

543
00:18:35.258 --> 00:18:36.238
I've dreamed it since my childhood.

544
00:18:36.238 --> 00:18:38.138
<v Voiceover>Now could that be a parallel or past?</v>

545
00:18:38.138 --> 00:18:39.838
<v ->Well, you know, the thing about dreaming</v>

546
00:18:39.838 --> 00:18:41.418
is you step out time.

547
00:18:41.418 --> 00:18:44.458
So you can say, "Okay, this is the 1930s."

548
00:18:44.458 --> 00:18:45.198
"Which year is it?"

549
00:18:45.198 --> 00:18:48.098
"This is 1941 in occupied Europe."

550
00:18:48.098 --> 00:18:50.558
Is that about what's happening then

551
00:18:50.558 --> 00:18:52.838
or is it about something happening now

552
00:18:52.838 --> 00:18:56.017
from a point of view that transcends linear clock time?

553
00:18:56.017 --> 00:18:56.798
I don't know.

554
00:18:56.798 --> 00:18:57.818
I know it's relevant to me,

555
00:18:57.818 --> 00:19:00.178
and I know that in my own sense of my life story

556
00:19:00.178 --> 00:19:02.758
the fact that I am dreaming recurringly, again and again

557
00:19:02.758 --> 00:19:06.377
in shifting scenes of adventures in Europe

558
00:19:06.377 --> 00:19:09.157
and in Britain in the 30s and during World War II,

559
00:19:09.157 --> 00:19:11.297
is absolutely fundamental to my understanding

560
00:19:11.297 --> 00:19:12.317
of everything.

561
00:19:12.317 --> 00:19:14.837
<v Voiceover>Yes, that is your alternate reality.</v>

562
00:19:14.837 --> 00:19:15.597
Your other ...

563
00:19:15.597 --> 00:19:17.196
<v ->It's one of the alternate realities.</v>

564
00:19:17.196 --> 00:19:18.117
I also dream of ...

565
00:19:18.117 --> 00:19:20.116
I mean, I became my first job was as a lecturer

566
00:19:20.116 --> 00:19:22.257
in ancient history at the Australia National University.

567
00:19:22.257 --> 00:19:23.996
The reason that I was drawn to that and offered

568
00:19:23.996 --> 00:19:26.337
that job was that as a child I used to dream in Greek.

569
00:19:26.337 --> 00:19:28.496
I'd keep a Greek dictionary by my bedside.

570
00:19:28.496 --> 00:19:29.837
I'm a lazy linguist.

571
00:19:29.837 --> 00:19:31.017
I'm a lazy linguist

572
00:19:31.017 --> 00:19:32.836
But I was given difficult words in Greek

573
00:19:32.836 --> 00:19:34.256
that I had to study.

574
00:19:34.256 --> 00:19:36.376
So we have different styles of dreaming.

575
00:19:36.376 --> 00:19:38.176
One of my patterns of dreaming is I dream

576
00:19:38.176 --> 00:19:40.356
into different cultures into different times.

577
00:19:40.356 --> 00:19:43.136
And it gives me specific leads that I am able to follow up.

578
00:19:43.136 --> 00:19:44.796
I mean, I'm a historian, I've been a journalist,

579
00:19:44.796 --> 00:19:47.776
I know how to do hard research, I like to check sources,

580
00:19:47.776 --> 00:19:50.716
I don't like fluffy new-age thinking about these things.

581
00:19:50.716 --> 00:19:51.895
So I check these things out.

582
00:19:51.895 --> 00:19:54.856
So in my dreams I am often given specific details,

583
00:19:54.856 --> 00:19:56.476
strange words, strange details,

584
00:19:56.476 --> 00:19:58.896
places, dates, et cetera, which I can check out.

585
00:19:58.896 --> 00:20:00.556
And I've developed this central practice

586
00:20:00.556 --> 00:20:02.096
I call dream archaeology.

587
00:20:02.096 --> 00:20:03.936
You're given some clues to a different culture,

588
00:20:03.936 --> 00:20:05.856
a different place, you can check them out.

589
00:20:05.856 --> 00:20:07.616
You bring the best of scholarship and science

590
00:20:07.616 --> 00:20:09.056
to bear on it and then you have something

591
00:20:09.056 --> 00:20:10.176
really interesting.

592
00:20:10.176 --> 00:20:12.116
Recently, for example, I've been teaching in the Baltic.

593
00:20:12.116 --> 00:20:15.456
I'm very excited by this, I was just in Latvia and Estonia.

594
00:20:15.456 --> 00:20:17.596
I've been to Lithuania three times.

595
00:20:17.596 --> 00:20:18.836
These are countries that have been through

596
00:20:18.836 --> 00:20:20.756
one of the most grueling nightmares of history

597
00:20:20.756 --> 00:20:21.696
that we know about,

598
00:20:21.696 --> 00:20:24.076
the Germans on one side and the Russians on the other.

599
00:20:24.076 --> 00:20:26.896
Trodden on by everybody, brutalized by everybody.

600
00:20:26.896 --> 00:20:29.016
Going to these countries to bring back the dreaming

601
00:20:29.016 --> 00:20:30.936
is an act of cultural soul recovery.

602
00:20:30.936 --> 00:20:31.756
<v Voiceover>Let me ask you a question,</v>

603
00:20:31.756 --> 00:20:33.775
when you have a people that have been so traumatized,

604
00:20:33.775 --> 00:20:36.856
and repressed and as you say, from each direction,

605
00:20:36.856 --> 00:20:39.856
do they often start losing their dream memory?

606
00:20:39.856 --> 00:20:43.436
Or are their dreams seriously impacted

607
00:20:43.436 --> 00:20:45.926
by these experiences collectively?

608
00:20:45.926 --> 00:20:47.856
<v ->I think that there was an effort to destroy</v>

609
00:20:47.856 --> 00:20:50.456
the imagination, I mean to destroy the collective mind

610
00:20:50.456 --> 00:20:52.296
and spirit of these peoples.

611
00:20:52.296 --> 00:20:54.116
I mean the sheer loss of population,

612
00:20:54.116 --> 00:20:57.456
the forced deportations, the mass murders of the population

613
00:20:57.456 --> 00:20:59.996
the effort to corrupt and distort the imagination,

614
00:20:59.996 --> 00:21:01.556
had a terrible effect.

615
00:21:01.556 --> 00:21:03.516
But bringing back the dreaming,

616
00:21:03.516 --> 00:21:06.296
and bringing back some ancestral traditions

617
00:21:06.296 --> 00:21:08.676
that transcend and precede all that horror

618
00:21:08.676 --> 00:21:10.176
is an act of healing.

619
00:21:10.176 --> 00:21:12.756
And I've found people flocking to my workshops

620
00:21:12.756 --> 00:21:14.096
to learn how to dream again

621
00:21:14.096 --> 00:21:16.436
and to learn how to share things with each other.

622
00:21:16.436 --> 00:21:18.535
Different phenomena in different parts of the region.

623
00:21:18.535 --> 00:21:20.336
In one of the countries people were very shy

624
00:21:20.336 --> 00:21:22.095
about saying too much in front of others

625
00:21:22.095 --> 00:21:23.596
because although they've been independent

626
00:21:23.596 --> 00:21:26.035
for 20 years now, it's only 20 years.

627
00:21:26.035 --> 00:21:27.536
And they all remember in their families,

628
00:21:27.536 --> 00:21:30.396
a time when it was terribly dangerous to say anything

629
00:21:30.396 --> 00:21:33.196
that you held true in the presence of others

630
00:21:33.196 --> 00:21:35.975
under totalitarian dictatorship.

631
00:21:35.975 --> 00:21:39.496
So I'm finding that a very interesting thing.

632
00:21:39.496 --> 00:21:41.095
And one of the things that's going on there

633
00:21:41.095 --> 00:21:43.476
is that we, in these workshops in the Baltic,

634
00:21:43.476 --> 00:21:47.235
including I, myself, are dreaming of authentic sources

635
00:21:47.235 --> 00:21:49.275
on the ancient traditions of these countries.

636
00:21:49.275 --> 00:21:50.676
When I first went to Lithuania

637
00:21:50.676 --> 00:21:53.236
I led a group journey for ancestral knowledge.

638
00:21:53.236 --> 00:21:56.216
I found myself talking to an ancestral priestess of Zemyna

639
00:21:56.216 --> 00:21:58.336
the great earth goddess of Lithuania,

640
00:21:58.336 --> 00:22:01.176
who insisted on speaking to me in ancient Lithuanian.

641
00:22:01.176 --> 00:22:03.696
Showed me some techniques of healing and divination

642
00:22:03.696 --> 00:22:05.816
which I have, was able to check out with the group

643
00:22:05.816 --> 00:22:08.776
and we found ourselves engaged in restoring

644
00:22:08.776 --> 00:22:10.756
authentic sources, goddess sources,

645
00:22:10.756 --> 00:22:13.115
of the old goddess tradition of the Baltic.

646
00:22:13.115 --> 00:22:14.996
Which had not died completely,

647
00:22:14.996 --> 00:22:17.536
Marija Gimbutas's work is an illustration of that,

648
00:22:17.536 --> 00:22:19.616
that it didn't die completely but has been buried

649
00:22:19.616 --> 00:22:21.176
and repressed.

650
00:22:21.176 --> 00:22:23.456
So you know, dreaming is a key to all these things.

651
00:22:23.456 --> 00:22:24.475
It's a key to soul.

652
00:22:24.475 --> 00:22:25.855
It's in our individual lives,

653
00:22:25.855 --> 00:22:28.495
it's a key to finding where our vital energy

654
00:22:28.495 --> 00:22:30.496
or identity might have gone because of trauma,

655
00:22:30.496 --> 00:22:32.036
pain, abuse, addiction,

656
00:22:32.036 --> 00:22:34.035
in our lives when we lost a part of ourselves,

657
00:22:34.035 --> 00:22:35.376
we lost that beautiful teenager

658
00:22:35.376 --> 00:22:37.556
or that young child went missing.

659
00:22:37.556 --> 00:22:39.096
Dreaming will show us how to get back

660
00:22:39.096 --> 00:22:41.875
more of ourselves and it will show us as communities

661
00:22:41.875 --> 00:22:43.915
how to bring back soul and heart and spirit

662
00:22:43.915 --> 00:22:46.436
to collective groups as well.

663
00:22:46.436 --> 00:22:48.316
<v Voiceover>And that's something that's needed globally.</v>

664
00:22:48.316 --> 00:22:49.096
<v ->It's needed everywhere.</v>

665
00:22:49.096 --> 00:22:50.356
<v Voiceover>The globe is being stressed</v>

666
00:22:50.356 --> 00:22:51.576
from every front right now.

667
00:22:51.576 --> 00:22:52.576
<v ->It's needed everywhere.</v>

668
00:22:52.576 --> 00:22:54.496
One of the functions of dreamers in traditional

669
00:22:54.496 --> 00:22:56.176
societies is to communicate,

670
00:22:56.176 --> 00:22:58.056
not just with their personal subconscious,

671
00:22:58.056 --> 00:23:00.116
and not just with each other,

672
00:23:00.116 --> 00:23:01.936
although dreaming is a social activity,

673
00:23:01.936 --> 00:23:03.596
we meet other people, we want to do that,

674
00:23:03.596 --> 00:23:05.896
but to dream with the animate spirits of the earth.

675
00:23:05.896 --> 00:23:08.216
To dream with earth and sea, and mountain and tree,

676
00:23:08.216 --> 00:23:09.356
and animal.

677
00:23:09.356 --> 00:23:11.176
And if we're liking that, we're liking a dimension

678
00:23:11.176 --> 00:23:12.776
of our humanity and our ability

679
00:23:12.776 --> 00:23:14.696
to survive and prosper on this planet

680
00:23:14.696 --> 00:23:16.216
and to maintain the balance.

681
00:23:16.216 --> 00:23:18.056
So dreaming is as important as that.

682
00:23:18.056 --> 00:23:19.456
We need speakers for the trees,

683
00:23:19.456 --> 00:23:21.096
we need speakers for the ocean.

684
00:23:21.096 --> 00:23:22.896
Not just environmental warriors,

685
00:23:22.896 --> 00:23:23.775
we need them too,

686
00:23:23.775 --> 00:23:26.315
but people who are actually, directly in contact

687
00:23:26.315 --> 00:23:30.055
with the animate forces and intelligences of the earth.

688
00:23:30.055 --> 00:23:33.255
This is one of the things that dreamers can provide.

689
00:23:33.255 --> 00:23:34.255
<v Voiceover>Beautiful.</v>

690
00:23:34.255 --> 00:23:36.235
And while we're talking about all of this,

691
00:23:36.235 --> 00:23:38.075
if you run into most people in the street

692
00:23:38.075 --> 00:23:39.455
and ask, "What was your dream last night?"

693
00:23:39.455 --> 00:23:41.355
"Oh, I don't remember my dreams."

694
00:23:41.355 --> 00:23:43.775
And a part of that is because of the shock

695
00:23:43.775 --> 00:23:48.155
of a culture in which work is put above everything else

696
00:23:48.155 --> 00:23:50.054
and we shock ourselves awake in the morning,

697
00:23:50.054 --> 00:23:52.095
slam down the first cup of tea or coffee

698
00:23:52.095 --> 00:23:53.695
and go on about it.

699
00:23:53.695 --> 00:23:55.755
Because we don't value the dreams,

700
00:23:55.755 --> 00:23:58.535
we haven't instructed ourselves to bring our dreams to us.

701
00:23:58.535 --> 00:24:02.875
We have this kind of mass amnesia about our dreams.

702
00:24:02.875 --> 00:24:05.255
So you have ways in which to help people

703
00:24:05.255 --> 00:24:07.235
retrieve dreams and I love it.

704
00:24:07.235 --> 00:24:10.295
One of the chapters, The Place of Lost and Found Dreams,

705
00:24:10.295 --> 00:24:14.034
(laughs) let's talk about that a little bit.

706
00:24:14.034 --> 00:24:16.302
<v ->It started for me one morning when I didn't remember</v>

707
00:24:16.302 --> 00:24:17.182
any of my own dreams.

708
00:24:17.182 --> 00:24:18.062
I thought, "This is no good.

709
00:24:18.062 --> 00:24:19.902
"Robert the great dreamer, where are your dreams?"

710
00:24:19.902 --> 00:24:22.742
So I decided to see what I could do about that

711
00:24:22.742 --> 00:24:24.342
and I found myself going to a place

712
00:24:24.342 --> 00:24:27.322
like the greatest video store you could possibly imagine.

713
00:24:27.322 --> 00:24:28.282
It's a wide awake dream.

714
00:24:28.282 --> 00:24:30.022
I'm lying in bed and I'm finding myself

715
00:24:30.022 --> 00:24:32.862
crossing the threshold, which is like a flowerbed

716
00:24:32.862 --> 00:24:35.302
that is also a doormat to this fantastic sort of

717
00:24:35.302 --> 00:24:36.922
cosmic video store,

718
00:24:36.922 --> 00:24:39.162
where I'm received by this attendent.

719
00:24:39.162 --> 00:24:41.562
And I'm shown file upon file, rank upon rank

720
00:24:41.562 --> 00:24:43.842
of DVDs from categories, you know,

721
00:24:43.842 --> 00:24:45.922
family, adult, drama, thriller,

722
00:24:45.922 --> 00:24:48.482
and categories we don't have in ordinary video stores.

723
00:24:48.482 --> 00:24:50.462
All my dreams.

724
00:24:50.462 --> 00:24:54.161
And I find in the waking dream I can select a DVD

725
00:24:54.161 --> 00:24:56.822
and play it and then it's a sense around movie

726
00:24:56.822 --> 00:24:57.922
and I enter it, et cetera.

727
00:24:57.922 --> 00:25:00.422
And I notice in this cosmic video store,

728
00:25:00.422 --> 00:25:01.902
the whole section devoted to my dreams

729
00:25:01.902 --> 00:25:03.602
with other people, dreams I've shared with friends,

730
00:25:03.602 --> 00:25:05.382
adventures I've had with other people.

731
00:25:05.382 --> 00:25:08.282
so this is one of the locations I've discovered

732
00:25:08.282 --> 00:25:11.021
we could learn to go to to look for our lost dreams

733
00:25:11.021 --> 00:25:13.542
another version would be the cinema of lost dreams,

734
00:25:13.542 --> 00:25:15.241
or the post office of lost dreams

735
00:25:15.241 --> 00:25:17.502
where you pick up the mail that you haven't been collecting.

736
00:25:17.502 --> 00:25:19.602
So in some of the workshops, and in the book,

737
00:25:19.602 --> 00:25:21.441
I suggest you can do this at home.

738
00:25:21.441 --> 00:25:23.162
I encourage people to go to a space

739
00:25:23.162 --> 00:25:24.982
where they can pick up some of the dream messages

740
00:25:24.982 --> 00:25:26.822
that they've been losing.

741
00:25:26.822 --> 00:25:28.760
<v Voiceover>I think that's an excellent idea</v>

742
00:25:28.760 --> 00:25:31.560
and I think one of the problems or challenges

743
00:25:31.560 --> 00:25:34.637
that certainly more Western cultures likely have

744
00:25:34.637 --> 00:25:36.037
wherever you have a dominance of logic

745
00:25:36.037 --> 00:25:37.238
and left-brain thinking,

746
00:25:37.238 --> 00:25:39.938
is this question as to,

747
00:25:39.938 --> 00:25:42.778
"Oh but what if I'm just making up everything."

748
00:25:42.778 --> 00:25:44.698
When you talk about taking this information

749
00:25:44.698 --> 00:25:46.298
and taking action on it,

750
00:25:46.298 --> 00:25:47.578
the question arises,

751
00:25:47.578 --> 00:25:49.677
"What if I'm just making it all up?"

752
00:25:49.677 --> 00:25:50.718
<v ->But I love making it up.</v>

753
00:25:50.718 --> 00:25:52.297
I mean we have a song we sing in the workshops,

754
00:25:52.297 --> 00:25:53.638
"Make it up as you go along,

755
00:25:53.638 --> 00:25:55.078
"The way will show the way."

756
00:25:55.078 --> 00:25:56.337
I mean, children understand this,

757
00:25:56.337 --> 00:25:57.998
the magic of making things up.

758
00:25:57.998 --> 00:26:00.218
It's about bringing back the art of imagination.

759
00:26:00.218 --> 00:26:02.258
Real shamans are masters of imagination

760
00:26:02.258 --> 00:26:04.138
and suggestion.

761
00:26:04.138 --> 00:26:07.088
Rabindranath Tagore said, with a poet's clarity,

762
00:26:07.088 --> 00:26:08.873
he said the stronger the imagination,

763
00:26:08.873 --> 00:26:10.953
the less imaginary the results.

764
00:26:10.953 --> 00:26:13.333
So a lot of this is about learning to make it up.

765
00:26:13.333 --> 00:26:16.113
It's a story from history in active dreaming

766
00:26:16.113 --> 00:26:18.013
which you may recognize,

767
00:26:18.013 --> 00:26:20.854
as it involves a famous Viennese psychiatrist called

768
00:26:20.854 --> 00:26:21.714
Victor Frankel.

769
00:26:21.714 --> 00:26:23.153
<v Voiceover>Yes, it's a beautiful story.</v>

770
00:26:23.153 --> 00:26:25.514
<v ->He was in Auschwitz during World War II.</v>

771
00:26:25.514 --> 00:26:27.633
He's reduced to a skeleton with a tattoo on his arm,

772
00:26:27.633 --> 00:26:29.313
there's no possibility of any hope,

773
00:26:29.313 --> 00:26:31.153
he can be killed at any moment.

774
00:26:31.153 --> 00:26:33.373
His world smells of blood and excrement.

775
00:26:33.373 --> 00:26:37.013
And he decides in the situation to grow a vision in his mind

776
00:26:37.013 --> 00:26:39.313
an impossible vision, to make something up.

777
00:26:39.313 --> 00:26:41.693
He makes up in his imagination,

778
00:26:41.693 --> 00:26:44.413
a vision of a world in which the Nazis are past history.

779
00:26:44.413 --> 00:26:47.493
In which he is comfortably, comfortably well-fed

780
00:26:47.493 --> 00:26:49.834
and well-dressed in a pleasant auditorium

781
00:26:49.834 --> 00:26:51.774
with well-upholstered seats,

782
00:26:51.774 --> 00:26:53.694
giving a lecture on the psychology

783
00:26:53.694 --> 00:26:55.253
of the concentration camps.

784
00:26:55.253 --> 00:26:57.173
Not only has he survived,

785
00:26:57.173 --> 00:26:59.273
but as a psychiatrist, an original mind,

786
00:26:59.273 --> 00:27:01.334
he is making sense and philosophy

787
00:27:01.334 --> 00:27:03.274
